{
  "response_text": "The average cumulative number of livestock destocked across all households starts at zero and rises sharply during the initial phase of the simulation. By approximately time step 20, the mean destock total reaches around 75 livestock units. From time step 20 onwards, the rate of increase moderates, though the cumulative total continues to rise through to time step 100. There is significant divergence among simulation runs throughout the 100 steps. One simulation run exhibits a consistently higher trajectory, reaching a cumulative destock total of roughly 172 by the end of the simulation. In contrast, several other runs stabilize earlier, remaining in the range of 60 to 80 cumulative livestock units for the remainder of the simulation period. This divergence in cumulative destocking suggests variability in household decision-making or environmental conditions across the different simulation iterations, leading to distinct long-term outcomes regarding herd management and resource utilization."
}

